Hi Thomas,

In 3.4 the flow-route protocol statement (flow component) is treated as a list. While the standard allows all kinds of ranges exactly like it does for port numbers.

This is not really a bug - we just noticed that it is impossible to have a configuration like below to announce a route with protocol matching like it works with ports (ranges of protocols):

For example:

```
     route {
       match {
            source 10.12.255.0/24;
            destination 10.11.255.0/24;
            source-port =3 =4 >200&<210;
            protocol =3 =4 >200&<210;
       }
       then {
         accept;
       }
```

in the configuration/ancient.py we hacked this in order to have the protocol be treated like ports... (with all the drawbacks): 

```
    def _flow_route_protocol (self, scope, tokens):
            return self._flow_generic_condition(scope,tokens,FlowIPProtocol)
```

however this may break named-protocol configurations like this (we did not test):

```
         protocols =tcp =udp >tcp&<udp
```

Many of the other flow components are also treated as a list which may be perfectly fine for most applications. But may not allow to use the full flexibility of the RFC itself.

Cheers

Christoph

